The geographical distributions of the different Panaspis clades present in Angola are in accordance with the main biogeographic patterns observed in the country (
Marques et al. 2018
;
Huntley et al. 2019
): 1) clear incursions of Central/Western African lineages ( P. cabindae and P. aff. breviceps ) through the northern areas of the country, extending considerably south through the more forested areas of the Western Angolan escarpment; 2) intrusions of representatives of southwestern/desert lineages ( P. mocamedensis sp. nov. ), crossing the Cunene River through the low elevation areas of southwestern Angola ( Namibe province ) and extending coastally towards Benguela province ; and 3) presence of more southern African/Zambezian clades ( P. wahlbergi and P. maculicollis ) through the higher elevations/plateau areas of central and southern Angola . Although not confirmed from Angola , the presence of a Katangan lineage of P. wahlbergi (“ Panaspis sp. Katanga 2” sensu
Medina et al. (2016)
, according to Bittencourt-Silva (2018)) on the Zambian side of the northeastern Angolan border, also highlights a fourth pattern, which is depicted by the intrusion of Katangan representatives into Angola through the northwesten and central western areas of the country, a pattern already noted in the recently described Trachylepis raymondlaurentiMarques, Ceríaco, Bandeira, Pauwels & Bauer (2019) (
Marques et al. 2019a
). More data are needed to fully address this topic in Angola , and especially to draw the borders (and contact zones), that divide these biogeographic groupings. However, certain areas, such as the abrupt separation between the higher elevation/plateau and the lower elevation/coastal areas in the center and southwestern regions of the country play the role of a barrier.

The description of P. mocamedensis sp. nov. represents the description of the seventh new species of reptile from the country since 2012, reflecting a steady increase of the numbers of Angolan herpetofauna, especially when compared to the almost five decades of no scientific activity in the country (
Marques et al. 2018
). The descriptions of many additional species from diverse taxonomic groups are currently being prepared by different teams working in the country, which, in combination with the discovery of new first country records, will certainly increase the already rich Angolan herpetological diversity.
